{"reviews": [{"written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 1, "timestamp_updated": 1471161983, "review": "Basically, if you're a digital pinball collector and/or looking for some variety, you might want to get this. I'm actually finding it fairly enjoyable.\n\nThere are 15 tables with a variety of themes for $20. That's a reasonable price per table. Yes, this is a mobile port, and it shows.\n\nThe physics are very basic (think Space Cadet, but a bit better), and the designs vary in complexity from very simple to moderately complex.\n\nYou'll absolutely need to apply anti-lag tweaks, and you'll probably also want to force AA/AF externally.\n\nThe 3D graphics are reasonable, but mostly nothing special. The art is quite good, including some decent animations in places. Textures are somewhat low low res and models are low poly, though. No fancy lighting here, but there are some reflections. The graphics/art of the game look much better when you're using the dynamic camera.\n\nThere is no controller support or key rebinding. The game doesn't even tell you what the controls are! But I just use JoyToKey, that's not a deal breaker in this case. Controls are left/right arrow for flippers, down arrow for launcher, space for nudge (just upward), C for camera change. R switches to portrait orientation.\n\nThere are 3 camera views - top down, angled, and dynamic.\n\nNudging, as mentioned, exists, but you can only nudge upward. This is basically enough for a nudge pass. There's a tilt system with warnings on a timer (I think), but it takes more than one nudge to trigger a warning.\n\nDead bounces somewhat work, but are not terribly reliable. Hold passes work on some tables.\n\nBang backs also work quite reliably on most tables.\n\nThe flipper gap is quite small, making slap saves rather effective.\n\nThere is multiball (possibly on all tables). I've seen up to 5 balls.\n\nThere are kickbacks that are on by default, can be depleted and re-raised, at least on the tables I've played.\n\nTables typically will have a mix of passive progressive elements and (simple) goal oriented modes. There are some video modes too. There's a decent variety of playfield elements, including extra flippers and playfields. Extra balls are awarded at certain score thresholds. Some tables have fairly involved progressions that are quite difficult (even for me) to progress through.\n\nMusic and sound effects are ok - nothing special.\n\nThe developers are not native English Speakers (company is based on Russia). This shows in some awkward grammar in places and accented speech clips.\n\nThere are working steam leaderboards as well as local high scores (yes, I set #1 scores on the 3 tables I've played through so far ;).\n\nEach table saves progress automatically, even if you kill the game or if it crashes.\n\nThere are various bugs I've encountered, some game breaking, but they're not too common. Some elements of some tables don't seem to work correctly. There's a glitch that causes serious game-breaking graphics issues occasionally if you open the help while in game and then immediately resume.", "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.602172", "timestamp_created": 1471068798, "recommendationid": "24875082", "language": "english", "votes_up": 59, "comment_count": "15", "author": {"playtime_forever": 432, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 65, "steamid": "76561197967388128", "last_played": 1471160713, "num_games_owned": 3371}, "voted_up": true, "received_for_free": false, "votes_down": 4}, {"written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 2, "timestamp_updated": 1470564691, "review": "The first time I've requested a Steam refund. \n\nI was REALLY looking forward to this. \n\nThe table camera views are terrible and only have very limited options to change them. THIS IS SIMPLY NOT GOOD ENOUGH !!\n\nMore damningly, the ball ballistics seem to 'float' and don't feel right either. \n\nThere are things to like with the themes and table design 