Naturally, I\u2019ve enjoyed some more, and others less. Computer pinball developers have in general, chosen for themselves a frustratingly Sisyphean task; to compete against those who \u201cport from reality\u201d tables loved (and played to financial success) for decades. But also to create, out of the blue, new tables that will be compared to every table ever made, computer or real, in both design and function. I believe that OOO Gameprom has generally succeeded. (Certainly to this player\u2019s satisfaction.)\n\nThe Pinball HD Collection (PHDC) Store Page doesn\u2019t seem to mention that this game offers FIFTEEN tables, and that might go far toward explaining what otherwise may seem to be a high price. What a player gets for $20US are some of the most interesting, creative and non-derivative tables I\u2019ve yet seen. Admittedly, at this point I\u2019ve only play a single game on most tables, but the need to produce this review weighed heavily on me. \n\nDesign wise, these are generally very beautiful tables, most having at least one additional playfield (and some have more than I\u2019ve ever imagined) but used wisely and productively. Pinball is in actuality far more than simply flippers and balls\u2026it\u2019s intelligent, wise, fun design. And as far as I can tell PHDC offers those aspects adequately (or beyond) in most cases. One concern seems to be is that this is a ported phone app. Not having ever played a game on a phone, I can only make the comment\u2026..\u201dWho cares?!\u201d I care about design. fun and playability, and I\u2019m mostly satisfied. Where I\u2019m not, I\u2019ll go to the next table and perhaps lose a very small portion of my \u201cinvestment\u201d.\n\nIt\u2019s said by some that PHDC has poor physics. But it has also been said that computer pinball may never match the physics of actual tables, and no doubt that\u2019s true (at least for now.) While I\u2019m generally loath to mention competing products in reviews, I think this example can be excused, and perhaps this alleged completion is itself a myth for these two games. Most of the community agree that Pro Pinball Ultra\u2019s Timeshock! table has the best physics currently available on any platform. I tend to agree. I\u2019ve played in the neighborhood of 2,500 games of Timeshock!, and when going directly from that table to PHDC, I don\u2019t even remotely experience a \u201cphysics funk\u201d. True, they aren\u2019t directly comparable, but TS costs approximately ten times as much per table, and has been in development since 1997! In PHDC the ball acts as I anticipate it should, and when I hit it, it goes where I expect it to, utilizing the \u201cmiddle flipper sweet spot\u201d extensively. For a game geared less for the elite player, and more for the beginning or average player (99% of the pinball market), it obeys the same laws of physics I do. I think that for the most part, complaints about physics are really more a request for a more realistic (or perhaps faster) speed. Personally, I\u2019d be much happier with PHDC if there were at least two game speed choices available.\n\nWhile it might be nice to make it clearer somehow that in PHDC, the ball is launched by holding the down arrow button, and flippers are operated with the left and right arrow keys, the game rules and instructions are expressed very nicely with a single (though sometimes complicated) graphic of the table currently chosen. (And it\u2019s available during gameplay.) Also, the instructions unfortunately downplay the versatility of choosing from a variety of camera angles during play simply by pressing the \u201cC\u201d key. A very nice feature that may need to be used regularly as the ball enters various playfields.\n\nAt this point it\u2019s not clear exactly how to play the two tables that utilize vertical areas of the gamefield \u2013 Pinball Fantasy and Pirates. Hopefully I can obtain clarification so I can edit this review. And I\u2019m currently not in a position to comment on the 3-D glasses aspect of this game, strictly from lack of knowledge. The leaderboards are adequate, but after placing 12th on six tables in a row I realized I needed to reset them manually by toggling between \u201cLocal\u201d and \u201cSteam\u201d to get accurate data. (But if you want to get in early with some high ranking scores, now\u2019s the time. After a single game on each I managed at least one #1 score, so it\u2019s likely YOU will too.)\n\nWho might enjoy Pinball HD Collection? Anyone will enjoy the creative layouts and original design. For elite players, on some tables some shots can be just too easy to make, and on some of the tables the games may just last too long. (Heck of a complaint, huh?) It\u2019s not for players that value franchise content over the very basic Zen-ness of pinball. It\u2019s also not for those that place achievements first over content. (At least for now. But as I\u2019ve said before, I played pinball for over fifty years before I even heard of achievements.) For beginners, I\u2019d don\u2019t see how a pinball game could be much more satisfying. I still play, and very much enjoy, Balls of Steel (no longer available on Steam) based on it\u2019s amusing and clever layout and design, and I feel fairly certain that if you too still enjoy earlier computer pinball, you will likely enjoy PHDC even more. I\u2019m an average pinball player, but I WILL be keeping this game, and playing it at least occasionally (possibly much more) for a break from the often \u201ctoo serious\u201d world of competitive pinball. I think PHDC is the perfect game for those who just wish to enjoy pinball at both its most basic\u2026\u2026AND more complex.\n\nThank you.", "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.549869", "timestamp_created": 1471049954, "recommendationid": "24866809", "language": "english", "votes_up": 26, "comment_count": "8", "author": {"playtime_forever": 1576, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 112, "st